    "gallery": [],
    "video": null,
    "content": "A very common narrative among internationals is that Nordic culture feels distant or difficult to connect with. During my first two months in Jyväskylä, I found myself unconsciously evaluating every interaction through my own cultural lens. I wondered why people avoided unnecessary small talk at supermarkets or why strangers stood so far apart while waiting at crosswalks. Everything initially felt emotionally restrained compared to the highly social environments I grew up in.\n\nThen, a completely ordinary interaction at a local community center quietly changed my understanding of how care is communicated here. I was trying to find a room for an integration workshop while carrying an awkward stack of printed materials, a winter coat, and several bags all at once. Somewhere between reading hallway signs and trying not to drop everything onto the floor, I became visibly lost.\n\nA Finnish woman stepped out from an office down the hall. There was no overly enthusiastic greeting. No personal questions. No dramatic expression of concern. Instead, she walked directly toward me, glanced at the stack of papers in my arms, and asked calmly: *\"Are you looking for the meeting room?\"* When I nodded, she immediately took half of the heavy files from my arms without hesitation. Then she quietly walked with me down two flights of stairs, led me to the exact room, opened the door, handed the materials back, smiled softly, and said: *\"Ole hyvä. Have a good meeting.\"*\n\nBefore I could properly finish thanking her, she had already turned around and walked back toward her office. Sitting inside that meeting room afterward, I realized something important: I had been searching for warmth in the wrong cultural format.\n\nSouth Asian warmth is often relationship-centered and emotionally expressive. It welcomes people openly and immediately. Finnish politeness, however, feels much more action-centered and practical. Space is respected. Emotional interaction is not forced unnecessarily. But the moment genuine help is needed, assistance often appears quietly, directly, and without performance.\n\nI slowly began noticing the same pattern elsewhere too. A stranger holding a train door open while balancing groceries. Someone helping lift a stroller onto a bus without exchanging more than a few words. A classmate carefully explaining an administrative process step-by-step after noticing confusion.\n\nThe kindness was there all along. It was simply being communicated differently. A Finn may not immediately invite somebody home for coffee after a first meeting. But if they promise to help with navigating a system, organizing an event, or solving a practical problem, they will usually arrive exactly on time and do exactly what they said they would do.\n\nBoth cultures are deeply genuine. They simply operate through different social languages."
