    "video": null,
    "content": "When I first heard about the Civic Orientation Course in Jyväskylä, I assumed it would focus mainly on practical information. I expected to learn about services, systems, rights, responsibilities, and everyday life in Finland, and we did.\n\nOver four weeks, we discussed topics ranging from healthcare and education to employment, civic participation, and Finnish society more broadly. The information was useful, but it was not what stayed with me most after the course ended.\n\n## More Than Information\n\nWhat I remember most is the atmosphere. Starting life in a new country often means carrying around dozens of questions. Some are practical. Some are cultural. Some are questions you are not even sure how to ask. Many things seem obvious to people who have lived in a place for years but can feel confusing to someone who has just arrived.\n\nWhat I appreciated about the course was that it created space for those questions. The instructors encouraged discussion rather than simply delivering information. People talked about paperwork that had confused them, situations they had encountered, challenges they were facing, and things they were still trying to understand.\n\n> Sometimes what newcomers need most is not another source of information, but a place where questions feel welcome.\n\n## Realising I Am Not Alone\n\nAs the weeks passed, I noticed something interesting. The course was not only helping people understand Finland. It was helping people understand that they were not alone in their experiences.\n\nAgain and again, someone would describe a challenge they had faced, and others would immediately recognize it. Maybe it was a confusing letter, an unfamiliar workplace expectation, a language-related misunderstanding, or a question about services.\n\nThe details were different, but the feeling was often shared. Listening to participants from different countries and backgrounds was one of the most valuable parts of the experience for me. Everyone arrived with a different story, yet many of our experiences overlapped in unexpected ways.\n\n## Learning Through Conversation\n\nI often found myself paying attention not only to what people were learning but also to how they were learning. Information is important. But information becomes much easier to understand when it is connected to conversation, experience, and trust. The discussion-based format made even complex topics feel approachable. Participants were not passive listeners. They were active contributors.\n\nThe course gradually became something more than a place to receive information. People began recognizing one another. Conversations continued during breaks. New friendships formed. Participants exchanged experiences, advice, and encouragement.\n\nIn many ways, it became a small community.\n\n## What I Took Away\n\nOne thing I have learned since moving to Finland is that settling into a new country involves more than understanding systems. Anyone can learn how healthcare works, how taxation works, and where to find information.\n\nBut confidence often develops through interaction, through asking questions, through sharing experiences, and through discovering that others are navigating similar challenges.\n\n> Confidence grows gradually, often through conversations rather than instructions.\n\nWhen the course ended, I left with new knowledge, but I also left with something less tangible. I felt more prepared to participate in the city around me. Not because I suddenly had all the answers, but because I better understood where to find them, who to ask, and how to engage. For me, that may have been the most valuable lesson of all."
